<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="193">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:147291" authority="Forel, 1887" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1887" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Xiphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Xiphomyrmex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xiphomyrmex</taxonomicName>
Forel
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="193">
This genus is very closely related to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24927" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetramorium" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetramorium Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tetramorium</taxonomicName>
, differing only in having the antennae of the worker and female 11- instead of 12-jointed. The scrobes of the antennae are well developed in all the species known to me.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="193">
The genus is widely distributed, being represented by a number of species in tropical Africa, Madagascar, the Indomalayan and Australian Regions and by one species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:145252" authority="Forel, 1887" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1887" class="Hexapoda" family="Formicidae" genus="Xiphomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Xiphomyrmex spinosus Pergande" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosus">X. spinosus (Pergande)</taxonomicName>
, with several subspecies, in the Sonoran Province of North America. The various species nest in the ground, like 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24927" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetramorium" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetramorium Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tetramorium</taxonomicName>
, often in very populous colonies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
